{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xpbo6TWe4CMpRGicKS72Xg","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-03'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd.md (multi-framework orchestration PRD, 2026-04-03)\n8\t  - architecture.md (existing v1 architecture, brownfield context)\n9\t  - prd-validation-report.md (validation report, 4.5/5 Pass)\n10\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n11\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n12\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n13\tdate: '2026-04-03'\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t# Architecture Decision Document\n17\t\n18\t_This document builds collaboratively through step-by-step discovery. Sections are appended as we work through each architectural decision together._\n19\t\n20\t## Project Context Analysis\n21\t\n22\t### Requirements Overview\n23\t\n24\t**Functional Requirements:**\n25\t38 FRs across 9 capability areas. The core is a driver abstraction layer (FR1-FR10) that normalizes 3 agent framework CLIs into a common `AgentDriver` interface with `StreamEvent` output. The workflow engine gains per-task `driver` and `model` fields (FR11-FR15). Cross-framework task execution uses explicit output contracts serialized as JSON (FR16-FR20). The Ink TUI gains a workflow graph component (FR24-FR30). Plugin ecosystem integration (gstack/omo) passes config to parent driver CLIs (FR21-FR23).\n26\t\n27\t**Non-Functional Requirements:**\n28\t18 NFRs across performance (driver spawn <3s, TUI update <500ms, health check <5s), integration (pinned CLI versions, backward-compatible schema, no plugin modifications), and reliability (crash detection <5s, atomic contract writes, idempotent re-runs). Single-user local CLI — no scalability or availability requirements.\n29\t\n30\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n31\t\n32\t- Primary domain: Node.js CLI extending existing Commander.js architecture\n33\t- Complexity level: Medium — one new architectural layer (drivers) on proven foundation\n34\t- Estimated architectural components: ~8 new (3 drivers, 1 driver factory, 1 output contract module, 1 TUI workflow component, workflow schema extension, model resolver)\n35\t\n36\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n37\t\n38\t- **Existing architecture** — 10 decisions from v1 architecture remain valid: CLI↔Plugin boundary, state management, beads integration, template embedding, verification pipeline. This PRD extends, not replaces.\n39\t- **Agent SDK** — Claude Code Agent SDK (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`) already in use for in-process dispatch. Stays as the claude-code driver implementation.\n40\t- **Codex CLI** — External binary (`codex`). Output format must be reverse-engineered from real CLI output. Auth via OpenAI API key or ChatGPT account.\n41\t- **OpenCode CLI** — External binary (`opencode`). Go-based. Output format must be reverse-engineered. Supports 75+ models with per-provider keys.\n42\t- **No programmatic SDK** — Neither Codex nor OpenCode expose a dispatch SDK. All integration is CLI wrapping via `child_process.spawn` with stdout/stderr parsing.\n43\t- **Ink/React TUI** — Existing TUI uses Ink 6 with React 19. New workflow graph component must fit the existing component architecture and 15 FPS render loop.\n44\t- **Workflow YAML schema** — Existing `workflow.schema.json` must be extended (not replaced) with `driver` and `model` fields. JSON Schema backward compatibility required.\n45\t\n46\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns Identified\n47\t\n48\t1. **Driver lifecycle management** — Spawning, monitoring, timeout, termination, crash recovery applies to all drivers. Must be uniform regardless of whether the driver is in-process (Agent SDK) or CLI-wrapped (Codex, OpenCode).\n49\t2. **Stream event normalization** — Every driver must produce `StreamEvent` objects. The TUI, cost tracker, and workflow engine all consume these. A driver that drops events or misparses output breaks everything downstream.\n50\t3. **Output contract integrity** — Cross-framework task execution depends on output contracts being complete, correctly serialized, and crash-safe. A corrupted contract means the next task gets garbage context.\n51\t4. **Model resolution cascade** — Task model → agent model → driver default must be consistent across workflow parsing, driver dispatch, and TUI display. A disagreement means the TUI shows one model while the driver uses another.\n52\t\n53\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n54\t\n55\t### Primary Technology Domain\n56\t\n57\tNode.js CLI tool — already built and running. TypeScript + tsup + Commander.js + Vitest. Ink 6 + React 19 for TUI. Published on npm as `codeharness`.\n58\t\n59\t### Starter Options Considered\n60\t\n61\t**N/A — Brownfield project.** The existing technology stack is established:\n62\t\n63\t- TypeScript strict mode, ESM modules\n64\t- tsup for build → `dist/`\n65\t- Commander.js for CLI parsing\n66\t- Vitest + c8 for testing/coverage\n67\t- BATS for bash integration tests\n68\t- Ink 6 + React 19 for terminal UI\n69\t- Claude Code Agent SDK for agent dispatch\n70\t\n71\t### Selected Starter: Existing codebase\n72\t\n73\t**Rationale:** No new project initialization needed. The multi-framework feature adds files to `src/lib/agents/drivers/`, extends `src/schemas/workflow.schema.json`, and adds Ink components to `src/lib/ink-*.tsx`. All within the established architecture.\n74\t\n75\t**New modules to add:**\n76\t\n77\t```\n78\tsrc/lib/agents/drivers/\n79\t├── claude-code.ts      # Refactor existing dispatchAgent() into driver interface\n80\t├── codex.ts            # New — wraps codex CLI\n81\t├── opencode.ts         # New — wraps opencode CLI\n82\t├── factory.ts          # New — driver registry and resolution\n83\t└── types.ts            # Existing — extend AgentDriver interface\n84\t\n85\tsrc/lib/\n86\t├── model-resolver.ts   # New — task → agent → driver default cascade\n87\t├── output-contract.ts  # New — serialize/deserialize cross-framework contracts\n88\t└── ink-workflow.tsx     # New — TUI workflow graph component\n89\t```\n90\t\n91\t**Note:** No project initialization story needed. First story is driver interface formalization.\n92\t\n93\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n94\t\n95\t### Decision 1: Driver Interface Design\n96\t\n97\t**Decision:** Refactor `AgentDriver` interface to support both in-process (Agent SDK) and CLI-wrapped drivers uniformly. `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` instead of `spawn()` returning `AgentProcess`.\n98\t\n99\t**Interface:**\n100\t\n101\t```typescript\n102\texport interface AgentDriver {\n103\t  readonly name: string;\n104\t  readonly defaultModel: string;\n105\t  healthCheck(): Promise<DriverHealth>;\n106\t  dispatch(opts: DispatchOpts): AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>;\n107\t  getLastCost(): number | null;\n108\t}\n109\t\n110\tinterface DispatchOpts {\n111\t  prompt: string;\n112\t  model: string;\n113\t  cwd: string;\n114\t  sourceAccess: boolean;\n115\t  plugins?: string[];\n116\t  timeout?: number;\n117\t  outputContract?: OutputContract;\n118\t}\n119\t```\n120\t\n121\t**Rationale:** The workflow engine and TUI consume `StreamEvent` regardless of source. `AsyncIterable` unifies in-process (Agent SDK yields directly) and CLI-wrapped (stdout parsed into events) behind the same consumer interface. Adding new drivers requires implementing `dispatch()` and returning events — no engine changes.\n122\t\n123\t### Decision 2: CLI-Wrapping Strategy\n124\t\n125\t**Decision:** CLI drivers use `child_process.spawn` with stdout line parsing. No PTY allocation. JSON output mode preferred where available.\n126\t\n127\t**Pattern:** Spawn CLI binary with `stdio: ['ignore', 'pipe', 'pipe']`. Parse stdout line-by-line. Each line parsed into `StreamEvent` or null. Yield non-null events from `dispatch()`.\n128\t\n129\t**Health check:** Three-step: (1) `which <binary>` to check installation, (2) version/auth check command, (3) return `{ available, authenticated, version, error? }`.\n130\t\n131\t**Crash detection:** Monitor `proc.exitCode` via Node.js `close` event. Non-zero exit yields `result` event with error classification. Meets NFR13 (<5s detection) — `close` fires immediately.\n132\t\n133\t**Rationale:** No PTY avoids terminal emulation complexity. JSON output mode gives structured data. Line-by-line parsing is simple, streamable, and testable with fixture files.\n134\t\n135\t### Decision 3: Output Contract Format\n136\t\n137\t**Decision:** JSON files in `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`. Written atomically (write to `.tmp`, rename). Read by next task's prompt injection.\n138\t\n139\t**Contract structure:**\n140\t```json\n141\t{\n142\t  \"version\": 1,\n143\t  \"taskName\": \"implement\",\n144\t  \"storyId\": \"3-1\",\n145\t  \"driver\": \"claude-code\",\n146\t  \"model\": \"claude-opus-4\",\n147\t  \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-03T10:30:00Z\",\n148\t  \"cost_usd\": 0.42,\n149\t  \"duration_ms\": 240000,\n150\t  \"changedFiles\": [\"src/api/users.ts\", \"src/api/users.test.ts\"],\n151\t  \"testResults\": { \"passed\": 12, \"failed\": 0, \"coverage\": 98.5 },\n152\t  \"output\": \"Implementation complete...\",\n153\t  \"acceptanceCriteria\": [\n154\t    { \"id\": \"AC1\", \"description\": \"User can register\", \"status\": \"implemented\" }\n155\t  ]\n156\t}\n157\t```\n158\t\n159\t**Injection:** Workflow engine reads contract, appends structured summary to next task's prompt as context.\n160\t\n161\t**Rationale:** JSON is universal across drivers. Atomic writes (NFR15) prevent corruption on crash. Version field allows format evolution. Contracts are debuggable — plain files on disk.\n162\t\n163\t### Decision 4: Model Resolution\n164\t\n165\t**Decision:** Three-level cascade resolved at dispatch time by `model-resolver.ts`.\n166\t\n167\t**Resolution order:**\n168\t1. Task-level `model` in workflow YAML (highest priority)\n169\t2. Agent-level `model` in agent YAML\n170\t3. Driver default model (hard-coded per driver)\n171\t\n172\t**Driver defaults:**\n173\t- `claude-code`: `claude-sonnet-4-20250514`\n174\t- `codex`: `codex-mini`\n175\t- `opencode`: inherits from OpenCode's own config\n176\t\n177\t**Implementation:** `resolveModel(task, agent, driver) → task.model ?? agent.model ?? driver.defaultModel`\n178\t\n179\t**Rationale:** Simple, deterministic, debuggable. Resolved model is logged and displayed in TUI. No magic, no indirection.\n180\t\n181\t### Decision 5: TUI Workflow Graph Component\n182\t\n183\t**Decision:** New `WorkflowGraph` Ink component inserted between Header and StoryBreakdown. Renders a single-line flow with status indicators, driver labels, and cost/time per node.\n184\t\n185\t**Rendering format:**\n186\t```\n187\t━━━ Workflow: story 3-1 ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n188\t  implement ✓  →  verify ◆  →  loop(1)[ retry → verify ]\n189\t  claude-code     codex\n190\t  $0.42 / 4m      ... / 2m\n191\t━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n192\t```\n193\t\n194\t**Status indicators:** pending (dim), active (cyan + spinner), done (green ✓), failed (red ✗). Loop blocks show iteration count.\n195\t\n196\t**Rationale:** Fits existing Ink component pattern. Single-line flow is readable for workflows up to ~5 tasks. Driver and cost info below each node gives full visibility at a glance.\n197\t\n198\t### Decision 6: Plugin Ecosystem Pass-Through\n199\t\n200\t**Decision:** Workflow YAML tasks specify a `plugins` array. Drivers translate to framework-specific CLI flags.\n201\t\n202\t**YAML:** `plugins: ['gstack']` on a claude-code task. `plugins: ['omo']` on an opencode task.\n203\t\n204\t**Driver translation:**\n205\t- `claude-code`: `plugins` → Agent SDK plugin options or `--plugin` flag\n206\t- `opencode`: `plugins` → `--plugin` flag\n207\t- `codex`: plugins not supported → warn and ignore\n208\t\n209\t**Rationale:** Declarative config in YAML. Drivers handle translation. No framework-specific knowledge leaks into the workflow engine.\n210\t\n211\t## Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules\n212\t\n213\t### Critical Conflict Points\n214\t\n215\t5 areas where AI agents implementing different drivers could diverge:\n216\t\n217\t1. Driver file structure and exports\n218\t2. StreamEvent production from different CLI outputs\n219\t3. Error classification from framework-specific errors\n220\t4. Output contract population from different agent outputs\n221\t5. Health check implementation per driver\n222\t\n223\t### Driver Implementation Pattern\n224\t\n225\t**Every driver MUST follow this structure:**\n226\t\n227\t```typescript\n228\t// src/lib/agents/drivers/{name}.ts\n229\timport type { AgentDriver, DispatchOpts, StreamEvent, DriverHealth } from './types.js';\n230\t\n231\texport class CodexDriver implements AgentDriver {\n232\t  readonly name = 'codex';\n233\t  readonly defaultModel = 'codex-mini';\n234\t  private lastCost: number | null = null;\n235\t\n236\t  async healthCheck(): Promise<DriverHealth> { /* ... */ }\n237\t  async *dispatch(opts: DispatchOpts): AsyncIterable<StreamEvent> { /* ... */ }\n238\t  getLastCost(): number | null { return this.lastCost; }\n239\t}\n240\t```\n241\t\n242\t**Rules:**\n243\t- One file per driver, named `{driver-name}.ts`\n244\t- Class name: `{DriverName}Driver` (PascalCase)\n245\t- Export the class as named export\n246\t- Register in `factory.ts` — never auto-discover\n247\t- Driver MUST be stateless between dispatches (except `lastCost`)\n248\t\n249\t### StreamEvent Production Pattern\n250\t\n251\t**All drivers MUST produce events in this order for a successful dispatch:**\n252\t\n253\t1. Zero or more `tool-start` → `tool-input` → `tool-complete` sequences\n254\t2. Zero or more `text` events (interleaved with tool sequences)\n255\t3. Zero or more `retry` events (if API retries occur)\n256\t4. Exactly one `result` event at the end (with cost_usd and sessionId)\n257\t\n258\t**If the driver cannot map a CLI output line to a StreamEvent, it MUST:**\n259\t- Log the unparseable line at debug level\n260\t- Skip it (yield nothing)\n261\t- Never yield a malformed event\n262\t- Never throw — unparseable lines are expected during format discovery\n263\t\n264\t**Cost reporting:**\n265\t- If the CLI reports cost → set `result.cost_usd`\n266\t- If the CLI does not report cost → set `result.cost_usd = null` (not 0, not undefined)\n267\t\n268\t### Error Classification Pattern\n269\t\n270\t**All drivers MUST classify errors into exactly these categories:**\n271\t\n272\t```typescript\n273\ttype ErrorCategory = 'RATE_LIMIT' | 'NETWORK' | 'AUTH' | 'TIMEOUT' | 'UNKNOWN';\n274\t```\n275\t\n276\t**Classification rules (in priority order):**\n277\t1. HTTP 429 or \"rate limit\" in message → `RATE_LIMIT`\n278\t2. ECONNREFUSED, ETIMEDOUT, ENOTFOUND → `NETWORK`\n279\t3. HTTP 401/403 or \"unauthorized\"/\"forbidden\" → `AUTH`\n280\t4. Process killed by timeout → `TIMEOUT`\n281\t5. Everything else → `UNKNOWN`\n282\t\n283\t**Driver MUST NOT invent new categories.**\n284\t\n285\t### Output Contract Population Pattern\n286\t\n287\t**After each task dispatch, the workflow engine populates an output contract. Drivers MUST:**\n288\t\n289\t- Set `changedFiles` from file modification events (tool-complete for Write/Edit tools)\n290\t- Set `testResults` from parsed test output (if detectable) or `null`\n291\t- Set `output` as the agent's final text response\n292\t- Set `cost_usd` from `getLastCost()`\n293\t- Never fabricate data — if information isn't available, set `null`\n294\t\n295\t### Health Check Pattern\n296\t\n297\t**All drivers MUST implement:**\n298\t\n299\t```typescript\n300\tinterface DriverHealth {\n301\t  available: boolean;     // CLI binary found on PATH\n302\t  authenticated: boolean; // Auth check passed (or N/A)\n303\t  version: string | null; // CLI version string\n304\t  error?: string;         // Human-readable error if !available || !authenticated\n305\t}\n306\t```\n307\t\n308\t**Check sequence:** (1) `which {binary}`, (2) `{binary} --version`, (3) framework-specific auth check.\n309\t\n310\t**If binary not found:** Return with `error` containing install instructions.\n311\t\n312\t### Testing Pattern for Drivers\n313\t\n314\t**Every driver MUST have:**\n315\t- Unit tests with real CLI output fixtures in `test/fixtures/drivers/{name}/`\n316\t- Test that `dispatch()` produces correct `StreamEvent` sequence from fixture\n317\t- Test that `healthCheck()` handles binary-not-found gracefully\n318\t- Test that error classification works for framework-specific errors\n319\t\n320\t**Anti-pattern:** Never mock `child_process.spawn`. Mock at the line-reader level — feed fixture lines to `parseLine()`.\n321\t\n322\t### Enforcement Guidelines\n323\t\n324\t**Code review checklist for new drivers:**\n325\t1. Class implements `AgentDriver` interface? ✓\n326\t2. Registered in `factory.ts`? ✓\n327\t3. `dispatch()` yields events in correct order? ✓\n328\t4. `result` event always emitted (even on error)? ✓\n329\t5. Error classification uses standard categories? ✓\n330\t6. Fixture-based tests exist? ✓\n331\t\n332\t## Project Structure & Boundaries\n333\t\n334\t### New Files (Multi-Framework Extension)\n335\t\n336\t```\n337\tsrc/lib/agents/\n338\t├── drivers/\n339\t│   ├── types.ts              # Extended AgentDriver interface, DispatchOpts, DriverHealth\n340\t│   ├── factory.ts            # NEW — driver registry, getDriver(name), listDrivers()\n341\t│   ├── claude-code.ts        # REFACTOR — extract from agent-dispatch.ts into driver class\n342\t│   ├── codex.ts              # NEW — Codex CLI wrapper driver\n343\t│   └── opencode.ts           # NEW — OpenCode CLI wrapper driver\n344\t├── model-resolver.ts         # NEW — task → agent → driver default cascade\n345\t├── output-contract.ts        # NEW — serialize/deserialize, atomic write, prompt injection\n346\t└── stream-parser.ts          # EXISTING — shared line parsing utilities\n347\t\n348\tsrc/lib/\n349\t├── workflow-parser.ts        # MODIFY — add driver/model/plugins to task schema validation\n350\t├── workflow-engine.ts        # MODIFY — use driver factory, output contracts between tasks\n351\t├── agent-dispatch.ts         # MODIFY — delegate to driver.dispatch() instead of direct SDK\n352\t├── ink-workflow.tsx           # NEW — WorkflowGraph component\n353\t├── ink-components.tsx         # MODIFY — add WorkflowGraph to layout, extend SprintInfo\n354\t├── ink-app.tsx                # MODIFY — render WorkflowGraph between Header and StoryBreakdown\n355\t└── ink-renderer.tsx           # MODIFY — add updateWorkflowState() to RendererHandle\n356\t\n357\tsrc/schemas/\n358\t├── workflow.schema.json       # MODIFY — add driver, model, plugins to task definition\n359\t└── output-contract.schema.json # NEW — JSON Schema for output contract format\n360\t\n361\ttest/\n362\t├── unit/\n363\t│   ├── drivers/\n364\t│   │   ├── claude-code.test.ts\n365\t│   │   ├── codex.test.ts\n366\t│   │   ├── opencode.test.ts\n367\t│   │   ├── factory.test.ts\n368\t│   │   └── model-resolver.test.ts\n369\t│   ├── output-contract.test.ts\n370\t│   └── ink-workflow.test.tsx\n371\t└── fixtures/\n372\t    └── drivers/\n373\t        ├── codex/             # Real captured Codex CLI output samples\n374\t        │   ├── success.jsonl\n375\t        │   ├── error-rate-limit.txt\n376\t        │   └── error-auth.txt\n377\t        └── opencode/          # Real captured OpenCode CLI output samples\n378\t            ├── success.txt\n379\t            ├── error-network.txt\n380\t            └── error-auth.txt\n381\t\n382\t.codeharness/\n383\t└── contracts/                 # Runtime — output contract JSON files per task/story\n384\t```\n385\t\n386\t### Architectural Boundaries\n387\t\n388\t**Driver Boundary:**\n389\t- Drivers ONLY know how to spawn their CLI and parse output → `StreamEvent`\n390\t- Drivers do NOT know about workflows, stories, TUI, or other drivers\n391\t- The workflow engine consumes drivers via `AgentDriver` interface only\n392\t\n393\t**Workflow Engine Boundary:**\n394\t- Engine resolves drivers from factory, resolves models, dispatches tasks\n395\t- Engine writes/reads output contracts between tasks\n396\t- Engine does NOT parse CLI output or know driver internals\n397\t\n398\t**TUI Boundary:**\n399\t- TUI consumes `StreamEvent` and workflow state updates\n400\t- TUI does NOT dispatch drivers or write contracts\n401\t- `WorkflowGraph` component receives flow structure and task states as props\n402\t\n403\t**Output Contract Boundary:**\n404\t- Contracts are JSON files on disk — written by engine, read by engine\n405\t- Contracts are framework-agnostic — same schema regardless of source driver\n406\t- Contracts are injected as prompt context, not as structured API calls\n407\t\n408\t### FR to Structure Mapping\n409\t\n410\t| FR Capability Area | Files |\n411\t|-------------------|-------|\n412\t| Driver Management (FR1-FR6) | `drivers/factory.ts`, `drivers/types.ts`, each driver file |\n413\t| Stream Normalization (FR7-FR10) | Each driver's `parseLine()`, `stream-parser.ts` |\n414\t| Workflow Config (FR11-FR15) | `workflow-parser.ts`, `workflow.schema.json` |\n415\t| Cross-Framework Execution (FR16-FR20) | `output-contract.ts`, `workflow-engine.ts` |\n416\t| Plugin Integration (FR21-FR23) | Each driver's `dispatch()` (plugins → CLI flags) |\n417\t| TUI Workflow Graph (FR24-FR30) | `ink-workflow.tsx`, `ink-app.tsx`, `ink-components.tsx` |\n418\t| TUI Activity Extension (FR31-FR33) | `ink-renderer.tsx`, `ink-activity-components.tsx` |\n419\t| Cost Tracking (FR34-FR36) | `ink-renderer.tsx`, `ink-workflow.tsx` |\n420\t| Driver Capability Matrix (FR37-FR38) | `drivers/factory.ts` (capabilities metadata per driver) |\n421\t\n422\t### Data Flow\n423\t\n424\t```\n425\tWorkflow YAML → workflow-parser → resolved tasks with driver/model\n426\t    ↓\n427\tworkflow-engine → model-resolver → resolved model per task\n428\t    ↓\n429\tdriver-factory → get driver by name → driver.healthCheck()\n430\t    ↓\n431\tdriver.dispatch(opts) → AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>\n432\t    ↓\n433\t    ├→ ink-renderer.update(event) → TUI renders\n434\t    ├→ workflow-engine collects events → output-contract.write()\n435\t    └→ next task: output-contract.read() → inject into prompt\n436\t```\n437\t\n438\t## Architecture Validation Results\n439\t\n440\t### Coherence Validation ✓\n441\t\n442\t**Decision Compatibility:** All 6 decisions are internally consistent. `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from Decision 1 feeds both workflow engine (Decision 3) and TUI (Decision 5). Model resolution (Decision 4) feeds `DispatchOpts.model` from Decision 1. Plugin pass-through (Decision 6) extends `DispatchOpts.plugins`. No contradictions.\n443\t\n444\t**Pattern Consistency:** All drivers follow identical class structure, registration, event ordering, and error classification. Output contracts are framework-agnostic by design.\n445\t\n446\t**Structure Alignment:** Project structure maps cleanly to decisions — `drivers/` for Decisions 1-2, `output-contract.ts` for Decision 3, `model-resolver.ts` for Decision 4, `ink-workflow.tsx` for Decision 5.\n447\t\n448\t### Requirements Coverage ✓\n449\t\n450\t**Functional Requirements:** 38/38 FRs architecturally supported. Every FR capability area maps to specific architectural decisions and source files.\n451\t\n452\t**Non-Functional Requirements:** 18/18 NFRs architecturally supported. Performance NFRs met by design choices (no PTY, Ink 15 FPS, atomic writes). Reliability NFRs met by Node.js close events, debug logging, and contract versioning.\n453\t\n454\t### Gap Analysis\n455\t\n456\t**Critical Gaps:** 0\n457\t\n458\t**Important Gaps (resolved):**\n459\t1. Added `capabilities: DriverCapabilities` to `AgentDriver` interface for FR37-FR38\n460\t2. Added `suggestCheaperDriver()` to `factory.ts` for FR36 cost routing hints\n461\t\n462\t### Architecture Completeness Checklist\n463\t\n464\t- [x] Project context analyzed (brownfield, 38 FRs, 18 NFRs)\n465\t- [x] 6 architectural decisions documented with rationale\n466\t- [x] Implementation patterns defined (driver structure, events, errors, contracts, health, testing)\n467\t- [x] Project structure mapped with FR traceability\n468\t- [x] Architectural boundaries defined (driver, engine, TUI, contract)\n469\t- [x] Data flow documented\n470\t- [x] All FRs and NFRs architecturally supported\n471\t\n472\t### Architecture Readiness Assessment\n473\t\n474\t**Overall Status:** READY FOR IMPLEMENTATION\n475\t**Confidence Level:** High\n476\t\n477\t**First Implementation Priority:** Formalize `AgentDriver` interface and refactor existing Agent SDK dispatch into `ClaudeCodeDriver` class.\n478\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01NyfUq8vxhxtYfk2LGppqTU","session_id":"be33ba5d-0e81-49c4-ae53-e69ac56cd1fb","uuid":"46bef876-4809-4180-a570-21e20501e930","timestamp":"2026-04-03T10:04:07.929Z"}
